Short version: your 404 page is loading a slightly different CSS stack than `index.html`, and that stack keeps the off-canvas drawer “present” at desktop widths—so its off-screen width gets counted in the page’s scrollable area. `index.html` hides that drawer at ≥1200 px, so you don’t see the bar there.

# What’s different between the two pages
- **CSS version:**  
  `index.html` pulls `assets/css/tuition-css-1.0.1.css?v=1.0.1.E`. fileciteturn1file0  
  The 404 loads `…?v=1.0.1.F` **plus** `assets/css/blog.css?v=1.2.0`. fileciteturn0file0  
  (So the 404 has one extra stylesheet and a different cache-busted build of the main CSS.)

- **Desktop breakpoint behaviour in your main CSS:**  
  In `tuition-css-1.0.1.css` there’s a desktop rule that **explicitly hides** the mobile UI at ≥1200 px:
  ```
  @media (min-width: 1200px) {
    .mobile-menu, .overlay { display: none !important; }
  }
  ```
  When that rule applies, the off-canvas panel can’t contribute to page width. fileciteturn0file1

- **404’s added stylesheet can override this:**  
  Because the 404 includes `blog.css` after the main CSS, any selector in `blog.css` that touches `.mobile-menu` / `.overlay` (or sets a conflicting layout rule) can neutralize the desktop hide—leaving the drawer rendered (albeit translated off screen). That’s enough for some engines to expand the scroll width. `index.html` doesn’t include `blog.css`, so the hide remains intact. fileciteturn0file0 fileciteturn1file0

# How to confirm quickly
On the 404 page in DevTools:
1) Uncheck the `blog.css` `<link>` (disable the stylesheet). If the horizontal bar disappears, that’s your override. fileciteturn0file0  
2) Or temporarily change the query param to the same CSS build as `index.html` (`?v=1.0.1.E`) and reload. If it fixes it, the difference is between E and F.

# Make it robust (pick one or combine)
- **Keep the desktop hide bulletproof** (best practice)
  ```css
  @media (min-width: 1200px) {
    .mobile-menu, .overlay { display: none !important; }
  }
  ```
  Ensure no later stylesheet re-enables these on desktop. (If you must keep `blog.css`, add the same rule to it.)

- **Global safety net** (covers any future off-canvas UI)
  ```css
  html, body { max-width: 100%; overflow-x: clip; }
  @supports not (overflow-x: clip) {
    html, body { overflow-x: hidden; }
  }
  ```
  Add this to the main CSS so any translated/fixed element can’t cause horizontal scroll.

- **Component hardening** (optional)
  ```css
  .mobile-menu { contain: layout paint; }
  ```
  This keeps transformed off-canvas layout from leaking into page geometry.

If you’d like, I can hand you a tiny diff for the main CSS and a 404-only patch so you don’t need to touch other pages.

